shared_text:
Lake County Virtual School
September 10 at 3:52 PM ·

Hello LCVS families!

We are officially announcing that after Sunday 9/13/2020 at 4:00 p.m. we will no longer be accepting new students for full time enrollment. We are aware that some of you are still awaiting information on your current enrollment status. Those who have completed the enrollment process prior to Sunday, will be counted as fully enrolled with LCVS. Those who have not completed the full time enrollment process by 4:00 p.m. Sunday, 9/13/2020 will have another opportunity for full time enrollment for the spring semester. We are still dedicating this week to answering and returning calls, emails, Facebook messenger requests and to helping families on location in our parent triage center. Thank you all for your patience and for your support. Click the link for more information https://tinyurl.com/y28m8rrz

shared_text:
Sawgrass Bay Elementary
September 3 at 11:36 AM ·

Our Shout-Outs continue today with another 2nd grade Lake Live teacher here at SBE!

"Ms. Clevenger is so patient and works well with her lake live 2nd grade students. She has good control of her classroom and is constantly communicating with us parents through classdojo. Lake live is the new normal now but it sure is not easy for the teachers who have to teach the younger children. Ms. Clevenger is doing such a good job! I am amazed of how well they follow her instructions and are adapting."

post_text: Las pruebas gratuitas para estudiantes para el coronavirus COVID-19 continúan el jueves y viernes de 7 a.m. a mediodía en East Ridge High School, Eustis High School, South Lake High School y Umatilla High School. Los estudiantes también pueden recibir estas pruebas en Lake Square Mall desde las 7 a.m. hasta el mediodía afuera en el estacionamiento y desde el mediodía hasta las 7 p.m. dentro de Lake Square Mall. Los estudiantes deben estar preinscritos para poder recibir las pruebas gratuitas del COVID-19 coronavirus. Aquellos que no se hayan preinscrito no podrán participar en estas pruebas gratuitas y serán rechazados. El distrito recomienda encarecidamente a los estudiantes que participen en esta prueba voluntaria, pero no es requerido. Para obtener más detalles, comuníquese con la persona de recursos de familia en la escuela de origen de su hijo. El formulario de preinscripción se puede encontrar aquí: https://mycw68.ecwcloud.com/portal8971/jsp/jspnew/preRegistration_new.jsp

post_text: The Florida Department of Health in Lake County in collaboration with the Lake County School Board is conducting immunization events form 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. on Aug. 4 and 10 at the Lake County Fairgrounds and Aug. 6 at East Ridge Middle School! The immunizations are free for children under 18 who are still enrolled in elementary, middle or high school. Remember to bring your child's immunization records, wear a mask and practice social distancing while you're there! If you cannot attend, immunization services are offered Mon. through Fri. at DOH-Lake locations. Call 352-771-5500 for hours and appointments.

We apologize for the confusion.) . https://www.mynews13.com/fl/orlando/news/2020/07/06/florida--districts-must-reopen-schools-next-month

post_text:
UPDATE:This idea is not a viable option given the Education Commissioner's recent executive order. Thank you for your feedback!

QUESTION FOR PARENTS: We've seen and heard lots of parent conversation suggesting an option that would have one group of students come to school two full days a week (Monday and Tuesday, perhaps) and then do virtual school the remaining three days. Another group at the same school would come a different two days (Thursday and Friday) and then do virtual school the other three days. That would lessen the number of students in the buildings at any given time and give us Wednesday for a full day of deeper cleaning. I see how that could work in middle and high school, but what about elementary school? Would it create a child-care problem for most parents? Would it be better to have elementary students come to school M, T, Th and F, and have only Wednesday at home for virtual learning? Curious to hear your thoughts.

Sherri Owens
Communications Officer
Lake County Schools

That would lessen the number of students in the buildings at any given time and give us Wednesday for a full day of deeper cleaning. post_text: In preparation for students’ return to school in the fall, Lake County Schools is offering three options: traditional in-school learning; full-time online learning through Lake County Virtual School; and modified-day learning, a combination of the two. We've launched a new website to explain the differences, and we invite parents to complete a form to let us know which option you prefer. Choosing an option doesn't lock you into a decision, but it can provide us with helpful information for planning. post_text: The Seminole County UF/IFAS Extension Office is offering a FREE Virtual Entomology Camp for registered students age 12-18 in Orange, Lake, Volusia, Seminole and Osceola Counties. Interested? Sign up soon! The deadline is Friday, June 26!
shared_text:
EVENTBRITE.COM
4-H Teen Entomology Camp

Ed Young, Seminole Soil & Water Group 4 Supervisor
June 24 at 3:45 AM ·

The Seminole County UF/IFAS Extension Office is offering a FREE Virtual Entomology Camp for registered students ages 12-18 in Orange, Lake, Volusia, Seminole, and Osceola counties.

During this virtual camp, teens will learn how to catch and identify bugs, preserve them, and start their own collection. Teens will receive their own pinning equipment and learn how to create an insect habitat. Finally, teens will learn from professionals in the community about the many jobs available in entomology.

The deadline to register is Friday, June 26th!

post_text: To prepare for the 2021 opening of a K-8 school in Four Corners and the 2023 opening of the Aurelia M. Cole Academy K-8 school in Clermont, Lake County Schools has proposed a redistricting plan that aims to relieve crowding and address projected student population growth. A School Board vote for tentative approval of that plan is scheduled for 6 p.m. on June 22, and a vote for final approval is scheduled for 6 p.m. Aug. 10. Public input is welcome at both meetings. Learn more: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1QA--w5GINS4qdFZi5ryhw6jOcvlrMDo2mWvbZctI8DQ/edit?usp=sharing

post_text: Gov. Ron DeSantis today unveiled a plan that expects schools to reopen campuses "at full capacity" -- the same day Lake County Schools held a brainstorming discussion about reopening schools with a core team representing teachers, support staff and administrators. The district will continue to comb through results from employee and parent/student surveys and feedback collected through social media. The conversation will continue, with opportunities for public review of a plan once it's drafted in July. The final plan is expected to be published by August.

post_text: Florida Department of Education is reviewing statewide civics education course standards. Public input is encouraged through an online survey accessible at https://www.floridacivicsreview.org. The survey will remain open through Aug.5. Stakeholders are required to provide user information before providing input. For further insight about the #FLCivicsReview, the department is holding a public webinar today -- Wed., June 10 -- at 3:30 pm. You can register for the webinar here: bit.ly/2UnMut8. If you miss it, it will be recorded and placed on floridacivicsreview.org. For more information regarding the FL Civics Review, see Chancellor Oliva's memo, here: bit.ly/3fexPIT, or visit floridacivicsreview.org.

post_text: As Florida gradually reopens and we continue our efforts to slow the spread of the COVID-19 coronavirus, Lake County Schools is considering possible changes to our ELC Summer Camp 2020, keeping health and safety as our top priorities. ELC Summer Camp is open to students who have completed kindergarten through Grade 5 at district operated schools. If you are the parent or guardian of a child who will have completed kindergarten, 1st grade, 2nd grade, 3rd grade, 4th grade or 5th grade at a district operated school by the end of this school year, please take our survey before 5 p.m. Friday, May 29, to let us know your thoughts on the possible changes. You may be asked to log into Google before taking the survey, and we ask that each parent take the survey only once. Find the survey here: https://forms.gle/xtFBDD9apJiqkmFG9

post_text: Free lunches and breakfasts will continue to be served to children up to age 18 at select Lake County locations throughout the summer. The distribution schedule will remain the same: 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. on Tuesdays and Thursdays. However, three schools -- South Lake High, Mount Dora Middle and Carver Middle -- will no longer serve as distribution sites because of low participation, effective May 19. Learn more: https://docs.google.com/document/d/17O-1ZMwntajweUcto4EmbsVLDLXQ-0c-Pm4H9iZotCY/edit?usp=sharing

post_text: Talk about closing out an unusual school year on a positive note 🎼🎤🎹🎬... Look who popped in to encourage Windy Hill Middle fine arts students during their virtual awards program. It's two-time Tony Award nominee and former American Idol Constantine Maroulis! Listen to the uplifting message he shared... and rock on!! 🎼🎹🎤
shared_text:
Windy Hill Middle
May 15 at 7:50 PM ·

Last night Mr. Tarquine's Fine Arts program had a virtual awards night. We received a message from 2 time Tony nominee and former American Idol, Constantine Maroulis to share with the students. Constantine was nominated for the Tony Award for his role in Rock of Ages on Broadway. Our last show was going to be Rock of Ages, which was cancelled due to school closure, so this was a meaningful message to them. He also references Frozen, our end of the year concert, and banquet, which were all also cancelled. He sings, offers advice, and made the students smile! Way to go Mr. T on providing this unforgettable experience for our Wolves!

post_text: Seminole Springs Elementary wrapped up Teacher Appreciation Week with two surprise visits during virtual staff meetings. Hamish Brewer, a tattooed, skateboarding principal from Virginia who authored the book, "Relentless: Changing Lives by Disrupting the Educational Norm" popped in on Thursday. And Donalyn Miller, author of "The Book Whisperer: Awakening the Inner Reader in Every Child," surprised the team today. Both authors are favorites among educators and their visits were a treat arranged by Principal Michelle Work, who added a few fun giveaways as well! #LCSThankATeacher

post_text: With all that our students are dealing with right now, they are still finding ways to be thoughtful, creative and compassionate. Here’s a great example from a Tavares Middle School student who is reaching out to say thank you to some very special people in our community. We think he’s pretty special, too!
shared_text:
Tavares Middle
April 18 at 11:21 PM ·

💫PATRIOTS MAKING A DIFFERENCE 💫
TMS PATRIOT Max Grinnell has been creating thank you boxes for mail carriers, Publix workers, Lake County Sheriff Office, and nurses & staff and a local hospital. Basically "all the people who are keeping our world running right now", Said Max. Creating an iced coffee and baking muffins to then deliver to people with a note that says "thankful for you." The outside of the box says "barista in a box". The design on the cup says "#IAmEssential" He has done this every week since the break. Pretty amazing! 🌠This PATRIOT is an amazing student.
#TMSPATRIOTSWORKINGTOTHEIRPOTENTIALANDBEYOND
#Patriotspayingitforward⭐

IT'S TIME FOR THE BIG REVEAL!

It's the time of year again when we, with the help of the community, choose Lake County Schools alumni who have made a significant impact on the community and our country to join other distinguished alumni in our LCS Alumni Hall of Fame. We are unfortunately in the middle of a health crisis that won't allow us to hold an in-person event to welcome them. However, please enjoy this virtual induction announcement of our 5 new Alumni.

We are pleased to welcome:

Margaret Berry Emerson - Leesburg High School c/o 1980
Dr. Dan Boggus - Tavares High School c/o 1975
Michaela McLean - East Ridge High School c/o 2015
Carey Baker - Tavares High School c/o 1981
Dr. Julia Nesheiwat - Umatilla High School c/o 1993

Please visit our virtual Hall of Fame at https://www.lake.k12.fl.us/our-district/hall-of-fame

post_text: Thank you for your patience today as we worked through Day 1 of our Distance Learning adventure. Our teachers and administrators are approaching this unique situation with understanding, flexibility and compassion. Here is an example of the compassion one teacher showed a student today. Christina Caldwell is a kindergarten teacher at Cypress Ridge Elementary. One of her students, Aubree, withdrew from Lake County Schools and enrolled in Hospital Homebound Education with Alachua County Schools while she is being cared for at Shands Hospital. But that didn't stop Ms. Caldwell from including Aubree in a video conference with her former classmates. It brought a smile to Aubree's face, and to ours. Thank you, Ms. Caldwell and all of our teachers, for making Lake great!

post_text: Distance learning in Lake launches on Monday, March 30, and schools are busy distributing Chromebook devices to students so they can access lessons online at home while school buildings are closed in an effort to slow the spread of the COVID-19 coronavirus. The district has about 31,500 Chromebooks for students to use at home. High school students received theirs earlier, as part of the district’s five-year plan to provide a device for every student in grades 3 and up. Distribution of the remaining devices began Thursday, March 26, and will continue on Friday, March 27, at elementary and middle schools. Additional days may be added as needed. Parents who have personal devices at home have been asked to allow students to use those for schoolwork so the district’s supply can stretch farther, particularly to families who otherwise would have no computer access for their children. Also to help meet the demand, the district is providing one device per household and asking siblings who live together to share.

post_text: Lake County Schools employees, did you know you can receive up to 5 counseling sessions for free?! Whenever you’re thinking “I’m in this alone” or “I just need to vent,” take comfort. There’s a whole support system out there through the Employee Assistance Program (EAP), a no-cost resource to employees and household family members, including dependents up to age 26 whether or not they live at home. Services are confidential and available 24 hours a day/7 days a week. Learn more about this #LCSWellnessWednesday tip at: https://www.lake.k12.fl.us/departments/chief-financial-officer/risk-management/benefits/health/mental-health

post_text:
It's "2020 Census: Statistics in Schools Week." Do you know what apportionment is and why it's important? Apportionment is the process of dividing the 435 seats in the U.S. House of Representatives among the 50 states according to each state’s population. The population is determined by
the census. At the conclusion of each census, the results are used to calculate the number of House seats to which each state is entitled.

post_text: ATTENDANCE BOUNDARY UPDATE: The School Board last night narrowed its focus to one option for the attendance boundary adjustments being proposed in south Lake County as we prepare for two new K-8 schools to open in the area. The district will move forward with presentations of Option 6A to the public. This option will greatly reduce crowding at Sawgrass Bay Elementary, while attempting to balance student populations at surrounding elementary and middle schools. While the focus has narrowed, board members have not taken a final vote. They are expected to make a final decision in June. Learn more about Option 6A, the new schools, and upcoming public meetings at www.lake.k12.fl.us/redistricting

This option will greatly reduce crowding at Sawgrass Bay Elementary, while attempting to balance student populations at surrounding elementary and middle schools. While the focus has narrowed, board members have not taken a final vote. They are expected to make a final decision in June. Learn more about Option 6A, the new schools, and upcoming public meetings at www.lake.k12.fl.us/redistricting

post_text: Some absences are unavoidable, such as when students have a serious or a contagious illness. But many absences can be prevented by identifying and resolving barriers to attendance. These can be related to transportation, bullying, inadequate supports for students with disabilities or a lack of engaging instruction. Talk with your child's teacher or principal about barriers to attendance, and let's prevent absences whenever possible. #SchoolEveryDay

post_text: Did you know...? Reducing chronic absence helps create more equitable academic outcomes, especially for children who live in poverty, experience discrimination and have disabilities. Chronic absence data can be leveraged to identify and address the school-wide and systemic barriers that impact our most vulnerable children who experience higher levels of chronic absence at younger ages. These children are less likely to have the resources to make up for lost learning time. #SchoolEveryDay

post_text: Good attendance contributes to students doing well in school and eventually in the workplace. The early school years are essential for laying a foundation for strong attendance and academic success in future years. By middle and high school, poor attendance is even more predictive of dropout. Each absence represents a preventable lost opportunity to learn in the classroom. We can’t afford to think of absenteeism as merely a lack of compliance with school rules. #SchoolEveryDay

post_text: In celebration of CTE Month and career education in our schools, we invite you to a showcase of our high school career programs at the "Follow Your Heart" expo TODAY at Lake Square Mall. Talk to students and staff about our programs, and for a $5 wristband get a "Taste of Lake County Schools" featuring culinary creations from our students!

post_text: It's #CTEMonth! What better way to celebrate than to stop by the Lake Square Mall on Saturday for the "Follow Your Heart" expo, where many of our College & Career Readiness programs will be on display. Talk to students and staff to learn more about these programs, and for a $5 wristband sample a "Taste of Lake County Schools" with culinary creations made by our students! Learn more: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1soAFWQDdF7g17_NfdZS-O2kCjrRmWuv2SPrLqZRMxhA/edit?usp=sharing
shared_text:
LAKESQUAREMALL.COM
Follow Your Heart Career Expo and Food Tasting Experience

Lake Square Mall
January 29 at 12:02 PM ·

Join us February 8th from 10am-2pm to experience some of the amazing career pathways that our Lake County Schools have to offer our students! Lake Technical College, Lake-Sumter State College and University of Central Florida will also be on site to tell you how to take the next steps to your future!

As part of this expo- Lake County Florida culinary students are offering a "Taste of Lake County Schools" food festival! A $5.00 wristband (sold day of the event at the center court kiosk-all proceeds go to Lake County Schools) gives you entry to an amazing "tasting experience!"

Leesburg, Florida Leesburg Area Chamber of Commerce Leesburg Partnership Lake County Florida Tourism Ro-Mac Lumber & Supply The Villages Word of Mouth Leesburg Public Library
